## Phase 3 – First Repository & First Commit (Start the Green Graph Today)

Click + → New repository  
Name it something simple: hello-github-2026 or my-learning-journey  
Make it Public and check Add a README file  
Create repository  
Click pencil on README.md  
Write something meaningful:  
"GitHub journey officially started March 2026. Goal: consistent learning, real projects, open-source contributions, and landing tech internships."  
Scroll down and click Commit changes  

Rule from today onward: make at least one commit every single day — even adding or changing one line counts.

## Phase 4 – Project Building Roadmap (The Real Meat – Build These)

Months 1–2 (Beginner)  
Personal landing page using only HTML + CSS  
Fully responsive portfolio website  
JavaScript To-Do List with localStorage save  
Rock-Paper-Scissors game  
Python console-based number guessing game  
Basic calculator app  

Months 3–4 (Intermediate)  
Weather app fetching data from free API  
Interactive quiz app with timer and score  
Random motivational quote generator  
Personal expense tracker  
Markdown live previewer  

Months 5+ (Advanced & Internship-Ready)  
Full-stack To-Do application (React frontend + Node/Express or Flask backend)  
Personal blog powered by markdown files  
Basic real-time chat application  
Data visualization dashboard with charts  
Simple machine learning project (push notebook + model from Colab)  

For every single project you make:  
Create a new repository with a clear name  
Write an outstanding README.md: project title, multiple screenshots, live demo link (use GitHub Pages), step-by-step run instructions, tech stack list, what you learned, challenges you faced  
Commit very frequently with good messages like "feat: added user login form" or "fix: mobile responsive layout bug"  
Always add a .gitignore file  
Pin your 4–6 best projects directly on your profile  
Enable GitHub Pages to get a free live website link for each project  

## Phase 5 – Learn Git Commands & Tools (Start After Week 1–2)

Install these (free):  
Git → download from https://git-scm.com  
Visual Studio Code → best free code editor  
GitHub Desktop → easiest way for beginners to commit/push  

Basic commands you will use again and again:

git clone https://github.com/yourusername/your-repo.git  
cd your-repo  
git checkout -b my-new-feature  
# edit files here  
git add .  
git commit -m "feat: added dark mode toggle"  
git push origin my-new-feature  

Then go to GitHub website → your fork → Pull requests → New pull request  

## Phase 6 – Open Source Contributions (This Is What Gets You Noticed Fast)

Search GitHub for: "good first issue" + your current skill  

Best beginner-friendly repositories right now:  
first-contributions (easiest possible first PR)  
freeCodeCamp  
awesome-python or awesome-javascript lists  
EddieHub community repos  
Any Hacktoberfest-tagged project (October gives extra motivation)  

Step-by-step contribution process:  
Find an issue you understand  
Click Fork on the repository  
Create a new branch (online or locally)  
Make one small, clean change  
Commit with a clear message  
Push your branch  
Open a Pull Request with good title and explanation  

Target: 1 pull request every 3–4 weeks → aim for 5–10 merged by the end of 2026.

## Phase 7 – Daily / Weekly / Monthly Habits That Actually Work

Daily (even 10–60 minutes):  
Make 1 commit (code, README update, learning note)  
Spend time coding or studying  

Weekly:  
Push real progress to at least one project  
Read code from popular open-source repos  

Monthly goals:  
Month 1 → 30+ green squares + 2 finished projects  
Month 2 → polished profile README + 4 pinned projects + first merged PR  
Month 3 → 100+ contributions + intermediate projects  
Months 4–6 → advanced full-stack/ML projects + 5+ merged PRs + start applying aggressively  

Track everything in a simple phone note or text file.

## Phase 8 – Pro Tips & Warnings You Must Follow in 2026

Enable GitHub Pages on every project for free live demos  
Add visitor count badge and repo star badges to README  
Experiment with GitHub Actions for basic automation  
Follow companies and developers you want to work with  
Star repos you like — GitHub recommends similar ones  

Warnings (serious):  
Never pay for fake stars, fake PRs, fake followers — recruiters and tools catch it  
Avoid every "paid internship guarantee" or "GitHub boosting" scam — all fake  
Do not spam tiny useless PRs — maintainers ban accounts fast  
Stay honest in your profile — backlogs, gaps, low marks are fine when you show real work  

